TableContextTimeStampAfterTable: {48597=Last meeting: Kentucky 60, Vanderbilt 58, Jan. 10, Nashville, Tenn. The Wildcats controlled the first half and held a 17-point lead in the second before the Commodores answered with an 18-0 run. The teams traded leads down the stretch, but Kyle Wiltjer hit a jump shot with 1:57 to put UK in front to stay. There was late controversy when Nerlens Noel's jumper narrowly beat the expiring shot clock. Ryan Harrow led Kentucky with 16 points. Noel added 13 and Archie Goodwin 12. Kedren Johnson had 18 for Vandy., 51204=3. Precious Points: Despite Vanderbilt's struggles, the Commodores don't make it easy to score. Vandy is allowing an average of 60.3 points per game this season. That's the lowest scoring average for Vanderbilt opponents since the 1950-51 team held teams to 60.5 per game. The Commodores are giving up 61.2 points per game in league play, and only two SEC teams have scored more than 61 points against Vandy. Ole Miss put up 89 in an overtime win. Missouri scored 81., 57399=Top 10 upsets: A November to remember, 36171=February 19, 2013}
textBeforeTable: VANDERBILT (10-14, 4-8 SEC) Coach: Kevin Stallings (271-173 in 14th season at Vanderbilt; 394-236 in 20th season overall) Last game: Beat Texas A&M 63-56 Roster | Stats KENTUCKY (17-8, 8-4 SEC) Coach: John Calipari (119-22 in fourth season at Kentucky; 522-160 in 21st season overall) Last game: Lost to Tennessee 88-58 Roster | Stats VANDERBILT AT KENTUCKY | WEDNESDAY | 8 P.M. | SEC NETWORK "I don't like to have the mindset that your back's against the wall, because when you play with that much pressure you're liable to play bad," Mays said. "I just want guys to play open, with a free mind, but to know that we got work to do." And though Mays doesn't want his teammates push the panic button yet, he also knows that time's running out to change this season's storyline.
